{{Multiple issues| {{news release|date=February 2016}} {{COI|date=February 2016}} }}
The '''National Children's Center for Rural and Agricultural Health and Safety''' ('''NCCRAHS''') is a part of the [[National Farm Medicine Center|National Farm]] [[National Farm Medicine Center|Medicine Center]], one of the research centers of the [[Marshfield Clinic]] Research Foundation.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://southwestfarmpress.com/equipment/farm-related-childhood-deaths-are-down-still-too-many|title=Farm-related childhood deaths are down, but still too many|website=southwestfarmpress.com|access-date=2016-03-10}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.hubcitytimes.com/2016/07/26/farm-safety-agricultural-health-national-childrens-medicine-center/|title=Making farm safety a priority|website=Hub City Times|access-date=2016-08-01}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/news/nation-now/2016/08/11/report-farm-children-safer-but-die-too-often-accidents/88583270/|title=Report: Farm children safer, but die too often in accidents|access-date=2016-08-15}}</ref> The center is located headquartered in [[Marshfield, Wisconsin|Marshfield, WI]]. and is primarily funded by the [[National Institute for Occupational Safety and Health]] (NIOSH), which is part of the [[Centers for Disease Control and Prevention]] (CDC). The director is [[Barbara C. Lee]], PhD.
== History == The National Children's Center for Rural and Agricultural Health and Safety (NCCRAHS) was established in 1997,<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Mulhern|first1=B|title=Saving Lives: the Marshfield-based National Farm Medicine Center and its director, Barbara Lee, work to reduce traumatic agricultural injuries and deaths.|journal=Wisconsin Corporate Report|date=January 2008|pages=26–28}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal|title = Partnering Strategies for Childhood Agricultural Safety and Health|journal = Journal of agromedicine|date = 2012-01-01|issn = 1059-924X|pmc = 4678869|pmid = 22490034|pages = 225–231|volume = 17|issue = 2|doi = 10.1080/1059924X.2012.658341|first = David L.|last = Hard}}</ref> one of ten centers funded by the National Institute for Occupational Safety and Health.<ref>{{Cite web|title = NIOSHTIC-2 Publications Search - 20038609 - National Children's Center for Rural and Agricultural Health and Safety.|url = https://www.cdc.gov/niosh/nioshtic-2/20038609.html|website = www.cdc.gov|access-date = 2016-02-17}}</ref> The mission of the NCCRAHS is to "enhance the health and safety of all children exposed to hazards associated with agricultural work and rural environments".<ref>{{Cite book|title = Agricultural Medicine Occupational and Environmental Health for the Health Professions|last = Donham|first = Kelly|publisher = Blackwell Publishing|year = 2006|isbn = 978-0-8138-1803-0|location = |pages = 391}}</ref><ref name=":0" /><ref name=":1">{{Cite web|title = Marshfield Clinic Research Foundation - North American Guidelines for Children's Agricultural Tasks (NAGCAT) - Welcome|url = http://www.nagcat.org|website = www.nagcat.org|access-date = 2016-02-18}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=|title=C|author=CHS Foundation|work=|date=January 2016|page=30|access-date=|via=}}</ref>
== Projects and products == *[[Agritourism]] began as a project to develop safety and health guidelines specific to children for farmers and operators of US agritourism businesses.<ref>{{Cite web|title = Integrating Safety into Agritourism > Home|url = http://www.safeagritourism.com|website = www.safeagritourism.com|accessdate = 2015-09-16}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.farmanddairy.com/news/safety-is-no-accident-agricultural-safety-awareness-program-week/320752.html|title="Safety is no accident": Agricultural Safety Awareness Program Week - Farm and Dairy|last=Woods|first=Katie|website=Farm and Dairy|language=en-US|access-date=2016-03-08}}</ref> In 2007 the center created their first set of safety resources for agritourism operators and launched a new program – Integrating Safety into Agritourism,<ref name=Agromedicine>{{Cite journal|title = Qualitative Assessment of Agritourism Safety Guidelines: A Demonstration Project|url = https://dx.doi.org/10.1080/1059924X.2013.766146|journal = Journal of Agromedicine|date = 2013-04-01|issn = 1059-924X|pmid = 23540301|pages = 107–116|volume = 18|issue = 2|doi = 10.1080/1059924X.2013.766146|first = Robin Tutor-Marcom MPH|last = OTR/L|first2 = Annette Greer PhD MSN|last2 = RN|first3 = Maria Clay|last3 = PhD|first4 = Tammy|last4 = Ellis|first5 = Tami|last5 = Thompson|first6 = Esther Seisay Adam-Samura|last6 = MPH}}</ref> housed at [http://safeagritourism.org www.SafeAgritourism.org]. *Cultivate Safety is a website for farm parents. It houses materials, resources, and content specifically geared toward parents of children who work, live, or visit farms.<ref>{{Cite web|title = About Us {{!}} Cultivate Safety|url = https://cultivatesafety.org/about-us/|website = cultivatesafety.org|access-date = 2016-02-17}}</ref> Out of the campaign grew a "Parent First, Farmer Second" radio ad series that received the 2013 Plambeck Award, Best Series.<ref>{{Cite web|title = ‘Parent First, Farmer Second’ radio ads win national honors {{!}} Hoards Dairyman|url = http://www.hoards.com/IB_Parent_First_Farmer_Second|website = www.hoards.com|access-date = 2016-02-17}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal|title = Effectiveness of a Media Campaign to Motivate Farm Parents to Seek Child Farm Injury Prevention Information Online|url = https://dx.doi.org/10.1080/1059924X.2014.891481|journal = Journal of Agromedicine|date = 2014-04-03|issn = 1059-924X|pages = 211–212|volume = 19|issue = 2|doi = 10.1080/1059924X.2014.891481|first = Tammy M.|last = Ellis|first2 = Barbara C.|last2 = Lee|first3 = David|last3 = Schwebel|first4 = Marsha|last4 = Salzwedel|first5 = Jason|last5 = Flyte|first6 = Scott|last6 = Heiberger|first7 = Barbara|last7 = Marlenga}}</ref> * Mini-grants are provided to organizations in the United States to support feasibility and pilot projects on prevention of childhood agricultural disease and injury.<ref>{{Cite web|title = Marshfield Clinic Research Foundation - Mini-grants|url = http://www.marshfieldresearch.org/nccrahs/mini-grants|website = www.marshfieldresearch.org|access-date = 2016-02-17}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|title = Funding Details: Agricultural Health and Safety Special Project and Pilot Study Funds (Mini-grant Program) - Rural Health Information Hub|url = https://www.ruralhealthinfo.org/funding/1632|website = www.ruralhealthinfo.org|access-date = 2016-02-17}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|title = Upper Midwest Agricultural Safety and Health Center – Ag Safety Grants up to $20,000 Offered by National Children’s Center|url = http://umash.umn.edu/ag-safety-grants-up-to-20000-offered-by-national-childrens-center/|website = umash.umn.edu|access-date = 2016-02-17|first = Joy|last = Archibald}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|title = Ag safety grants up to $20,000 offered by National Children’s Center – Vegetable Growers News|url = http://vegetablegrowersnews.com/news/ag-safety-grants-up-to-20000-offered-by-national-childrens-center/|website = vegetablegrowersnews.com|access-date = 2016-02-17}}</ref> * Model Policy is a voluntary guideline outlining best practices for employers that hire young workers. Information is included regarding the rationale for age-appropriate assignments, training needs for adolescent workers, ideal supervision, and mentoring by adult workers. * North American Guidelines for Children's Agricultural Tasks is a collection of guidelines to assist parents and others in assigning age-appropriate tasks for children (ages 7–16) that live or work on ranches or farms in [[North America]].<ref name=":1" /><ref name=Agromedicine/><ref>{{Cite web|url = http://www.childrenssafetynetwork.org/sites/childrenssafetynetwork.org/files/Rural_Injury_Prvnt_Child_Youth_Ag_%20Injuries_111711.pdf|title = Resources on Rural Injury Prevention: Child and Youth Agricultural Injuries|date = |access-date = |website = |publisher = |last = |first = }}</ref> * ''Nurture'' is the center's newsletter.<ref>{{Cite web|title = Marshfield Clinic Research Foundation - Nurture Newsletter|url = http://www.marshfieldresearch.org/nfmc/nurture-newsletter|website = www.marshfieldresearch.org|access-date = 2016-02-17|deadurl = yes|archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20160414203100/http://www.marshfieldresearch.org/nfmc/nurture-newsletter|archivedate = 2016-04-14|df = }}</ref> * Safe Play was a project that designed the first comprehensive guidelines for constructing an outdoor safe play area on a farm.<ref>{{Cite web|title = Marshfield Clinic Research Foundation - Safe Play|url = http://www.marshfieldresearch.org/nccrahs/safe-play|website = www.marshfieldresearch.org|access-date = 2016-02-17}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|title = 11 Ways to Create a Safe Play Area for Children on the Farm|url = http://www.ruralins.com/safe-play-areas/11-ways-create-safe-play-area-children-farm|website = Rural Mutual Insurance|access-date = 2016-02-17|language = en-US}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|title = Safe Play Areas {{!}} Rural Mutual Insurance|url = http://www.ruralins.com/farmsafety/safe-play-areas|website = Rural Mutual Insurance|access-date = 2016-02-17|language = en-US}}</ref> * Safety Guidelines for Hired Adolescent Farmworkers is a series of 7 posters giving advice on supervisor responsibilities for ensuring work conditions are appropriate and adequate, and also used as an assessment tool for teen workers. These guidelines are available in English and Spanish.<ref name=":0">{{Cite web|title = Safety Guidelines for Hired Adolescent Farm Workers - SaGHAF|url = http://www.migrantclinician.org/toolsource/resource/safety-guidelines-hired-adolescent-farm-workers-saghaf.html|website = www.migrantclinician.org|access-date = 2016-02-17}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|title = Marshfield Clinic Research Foundation - Safety Guidelines for Hired Adolescent Farm Workers (SaGHAF)|url = http://www.marshfieldresearch.org/nccrahs/safety-guidelines-for-hired-adolescent-farm-workers-saghaf|website = www.marshfieldresearch.org|access-date = 2016-02-17}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal|url = |title = Agricultural employers’ hiring and safety practices for adolescent workers.|last = Lee|first = Barbara C|date = 2007|journal = Journal of Agriculture Safety and Health|doi = |pmid = }}</ref><ref>Lee BC, Westaby JD, Benetti L, Chyou P, Peters M, Purschwitz MA. Safety practices for employers and supervisors of adolescent farmworkers (STESAF). Summer Conference of the National Institute for Farm Safety Inc. Wintergreen Resort, Wintergreen, VA. 2005; Paper No. T-05-08.</ref> * News Clippings data provides a source of injury and fatality data for researchers, academics, and government agencies. The center maintains the only publicly available database of news clippings data on injuries and deaths in agriculture, housed at [http://www.AgInjuryNews.org www.AgInjuryNews.org].<ref>{{Cite web|title = Ag Injury News Clippings|url = http://www.AgInjuryNews.org|website = www.aginjurynews.org|access-date = 2016-02-17}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal|last=Weichelt|first=Bryan|last2=Gorucu|first2=Serap|date=2018-02-17|title=Supplemental surveillan